    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="455"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.51/1028</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Appointed Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grey</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 13, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 884</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In a note addressed by Lord Curzon to the United
                    States Ambassador in London on September 13th,<note n="50" xml:id="d455fn50">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_484">p. 484</ref>.</note>
                    relative to the present negotiations for affording financial assistance to
                    Liberia, a copy of which you have no doubt received from Mr. Davis, it was
                    stated in paragraph four of the specific points to which it was thought
                    desirable to call attention, that two outstanding British claims against the
                    Liberian Government had been traced, one of which, for £44.18.9 was made by
                    Messrs. Wayland and Son, Limited, of Liverpool against the Liberian Post
                    Office.</p>
                <p>I have now received a communication from my Government stating that the Liberian
                    Government have informed the British Consulate <pb facs="0589" n="504"
                        xml:id="pg_504"/> General at Monrovia that this obligation has now been
                    discharged.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>(For H. M. Ambassador)<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. C. Lindsay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
